< text>
The best things in life always survive, including Atami Sushi.  We have been going to Atami since 1999, and this family run business continues to maintain high quality delicious sushi with a friendly comfortable atmosphere.  Michelle and Wiley always make you feel welcome when you arrive and they remember your favorite selections.  The sushi is always fresh, the service is quick, and Michelle always keeps the restaurant extremely clean.  They have had a tough time fighting through the Covid shutdowns, so if you are in the neighborhood and want some great sushi in a cozy and friendly restaurant, you should stop on by and pay them a visit.  Also, this is a rarity in SF, but they have several parking spots for those coming from farther away.<//text>

<Text>My favorite restaurant on the planet. I have eaten here with friends and family at least 50 times and always had an excellent experience. This is a small family owned restaurant with amazing and authentic Japanese sushi. Yes, the portions are on the smaller site but the quality of the ingredients and the love of the owners for their customers more than makes up for this.
On some nights the service can be slow but just bring time and you won't be disappointed. This restaurant is all about taste and flavor, unlike so many Bay Area restaurants that sell mediocre food in a hipster ambiance for the same price.</Text><pictures>None<//pictures><resp>None< /resp><GmapID>0x808580dc6e49ad11:0x60e45ffb6f3910a1<//GmapID></record>

< user_name>
Jennie Lin</user_name>
< response>
None< /response>
<time>1192306645441</time>< Text>
I agree with Ian H: great sushi without the obnoxious scene.  The restaurant is set back from Lombard Street, behind a little stone garden and, while not ornately  decorated, is quiet and clean.  Service can be a little leisurely (usually because Michelle, an owner, is the only one serving tables) but the food is great.  The fish is quite fresh: sashimi pieces are smaller than you see at most restaurants but it's good stuff.  I don't usually order rolls when eating sushi but Atami's rolls use interesting fish (say no to Alaskan Rolls of salmon and cream cheese!) and are presented nicely.  Great sushi restaurant in a neighborhood of hits and (mostly) misses.</Text>

<date>1565576786804<//date><pics>None<//pics><text>8/11/19

My family and I have been coming here for YEARS and I can honestly say, they hands down have the best barbacoa & carnitas. Although I will add that somedays their carnitas will taste VERY salty or underseasoned. Today though, they were both very very good.

I have never tried their asada, so I bought a single asada taco and was not a fan at all....it tasted like boiled meat. I don't know how to describe it but if you are looking for amazing asada tacos, this isn't the place to get them. I also ordered to go cups of rice and beans and I was horribly disgusted. The beans and rice both lacked flavor and tasted so so burnt from being in the metal cambros under the heat lamps. The rice was very dry as well and you could see grains of rice that were indeed blackish brown from being burnt to the sides of the pan. The beans also were sitting in there so long that a thick layer was dried on the cambro. Not a good taste at all.

I did order the meat, tortillas & drinks in one transaction and forgot to get the beans and rice and sent my husband. The first cashier was very nice but left on break and the second cashier was very dry and rude. Alfonso's needs to step up the customer service...it's not okay to behave that way to customers just because you are overwhelmed and busy. I was honestly more on the disappointed side today with my visit.

If I return, it will only be for the carnitas & barbacoa early in the AM to avoid upset workers & the lunch rush.<//text>< response>

We are locals and had a staycation on Valentine's Day. We couldn't have had a lovelier experience.  The staff was thoughtful and response times were great.  The room was beautiful!!  We walked into prepared tea, lit tea candles, a little board with edible flowers and chocolate covered strawberries.  This was unexpected and delicious. A form to select your breakfast is provided, with easy submission of simply texting a photo.  Our breakfast was cutely packed and waiting for us when we awoke.  We enjoyed our breakfast on the patio, overlooking the gardens.  Everything is locally sourced from honey to fresh juices.  You'll feel good about supporting this business and you'll have a great and relaxing time.

We couldn't have had a nicer experience and will absolutely be back.<//text>

< userid>
111979514165676292638<//userid>

< name>
Toby Johnson<//name>
<response>None<//response>< Text>
Tucked away in a lush garden setting on the side of a hill lies this wonderful retreat that focuses on connecting with nature and with oneself. We had a one night reservation so we got there right around the 3pm check-in time to make the most of our stay.  The staff was very welcoming and friendly. The property was smaller than I thought it would be, but the fact that the Inn is only a 6 room bed and breakfast adds to the intimacy of the place, and made it feel so cozy. The property and our room was so clean, and the Covid measures they had in place felt very safe and made me feel comfortable. We stayed in the Rosemary room which is one of the rooms on the bottom level. The room had an outside deck to sit at which overlooked the outside gardens which is a shared common space for the other rooms as well. A couple of guests were enjoying the outside table next to the water feature the next morning, but that did not bother me, and the deck still felt fairly private at night. The garden was lovely to walk through and you can feel free to clip some fresh herbs from the garden to enjoy at home. There are many succulent plants growing there, and you can purchase them to take home, with the smallest plants starting at two dollars.
The holistic vibe continues with a focus on the healing energy of nature such as through crystals, for instance there is a large selenite globe in your room, and you can purchase other crystals from the small display cases in the lobby. I purchased some honey, fresh preserves, and bath salts to take home. The room was very comfortable with a sitting area, and a nice kitchenette including a microwave, dishes, and utensils.
The bed was very comfy and I slept wonderfully. The humidifier, and the sound machine, which you could change to hear sounds of the ocean, rainfall, etc, added to the relaxing vibe. There was a very large flat screen TV, but did not feel the need to turn it on because it was so peaceful just listening to the sound machine, or my bluetooth speaker I brought from home, or the croaking of the frogs out in the garden at night. The included herbal flower tea bath set was a great way to end the day in the deep soak bathtub, tea light candles are also provided to add to the ambiance. The included fresh herbal tea setup served in a clear glass kettle that is kept warm over a tea light burner, as well as a snack plate with dried fruits, nuts, and organic chocolates, is a lovely welcome in your room upon check in. Breakfast is delivered outside your room in the morning. It is not a hot breakfast, but was still a very delicious assortment of items such as yogurt parfaits, bakery goods, fruit, and boiled eggs, which you can pre-select the night before. In addition to the many complimentary offers, the availability of the various add-ons is a great way to enhance the experience of your stay. For my birthday stay here I added the herbal foot soak which is enjoyed out on the deck, and was served with more hot herbal tea to enjoy. I also added the Full Moon package which included extras such as a large charcuterie board, sparkling wine, a large fresh flower bouquet from the garden, a meditation kit including items such as a selenite stone, and complementary late checkout.  The Inn is a short walk to Moonlight Beach, be sure to stop at the very unique rock garden on your way there. The nearby Cottonwood Creek park was lovely to stroll through, and downtown Encinitas is a short walk away as well. Just be advised that there is no sidewalk from the Inn down to the street corner, so be aware of cars, or when walking at night. I walked to nearby Chiko, they served delicious Asian fusion cuisine and brought it back to our room, but you can also have food delivered to the Inn from one of the nearby restaurants if you don‚Äôt want to walk at night. I would highly recommend the Inn at Moonlight Beach for anyone looking for a peaceful place to relax and recharge!</Text>

<Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
PURE MAGIC. If you are looking for a sacred, grounding, rejuvenating, relaxing, beautifully energetic space filled with love, grace and peace‚Ä¶.this is your spot. This hidden gem will truly amaze you and let me share why‚Ä¶

I was intrigued to learn from our lovely hostess (who actually is the amazing architect of this sacred space) that this Inn actually meets WELL building standards which means that the space itself enhances human heath and well-being through design and operational features of the environment (such as the biodynamic gardens, water, air, atmosphere and lighting). WELL building standards look into the connection between the physical building and the wellbeing of whomever inherits the space. SO COOL and inspirational that buildings can actually leave people and the environment better off than before they spent time in the building.

THE COMMON SPACE: One of my favorite parts of the space is the communal living room and kitchen hang out area. This space is soooo lovely, inviting and calming. It has an amazing indoor-outdoor feel to it with the ambiance sounds and decor that made me feel very connected to nature. There are all sorts of healing herbal teas, spices, roots and herbs, snacks, fruit and vegetables from the on-site gardens and the most amazing coffee! It is a help-yourself style kitchen and so you feel like you are home, which is such a unique experience for an Inn environment. There is also an extensive book shelf with a range of books that bring insight, awareness and inspiration to your life! The yoga deck is another feature that I truly appreciated having available.

THE ROOM: #FengShuiAllDay! WOW - another amazing, oh so cozy and comforting, beautiful space. I stayed in the Sage room - Ocean view balcony ‚Ä¶ need I say any more? Upon entering the room there was hot tea and aromatherapy awaiting my arrival, which was so welcoming. Aside from the space being amazing, the bed and pillows were SO comfortable! I bring my own pillow with me everywhere and I actually forgot my pillow and I was so pleased that these pillows beat my own pillow times 10! So luxurious. I had everything I needed! In the morning a picnic basket filled with all sorts of delicious complimentary breakfast goodies was waiting on my doorstep! This was a perfect place for a romantic stay with my boyfriend :) I‚Äôd also consider coming here for a weekend meditation retreat or for a rejuvenation weekend.

I had such an experience of being welcomed and at home in the grace of contribution and love from our exceptional hostess, the lovely inn keeper and from the environment itself. Inn at Moonlight deserves a 10 star rating from me!!! :)

I hope anyone reading this enjoys his or her stay as much as I did! You will be left feeling peaceful, connected and powerful after your stay. Enjoy! :)</review>

< review>
I have been here several times and never a single time I was let down. I usually order the 3 course menu ($60) including appetizer, pasta, and an entree. Yes the portion is smaller than a la carte, but neither my partner nor I felt we needed to order more. The Chef is also good at making soup. It‚Äôs so good I was seriously considering order a regular bowl.

Wine by glass is quite pricey, usually between $12-15/glass. We decided to go with a bottle that fits within the budget we are more comfortable with.

It‚Äôs a family owned restaurant so maybe that‚Äôs why it feels even more homier.  The paintings on the walls were painted by the mother of the chef.  It does get busy on the weekends. It‚Äôll make the whole dining experience even better if they can reduce the number of tables in the restaurant. Our table was really close to other tables it reminded me of my dining experience in Paris.< /review>

< text>
I had one of the best meals and dining experiences at Persephone last night! It is one of those newer gems Santa Cruz is fortunate enough to have open up. I think this place will be around for the long haul. They have all the important pieces in place: a gifted visionary chef, great menu with local and sustainable ingredients, well trained wait staff, fabulous management, beautiful decor and ambiance, good volume levels, and a desire to continue to grow and evolve to make things better and better (even while they're clearly already doing an amazing job)! I am delighted to have finally made it I'm for a memorable meal. I look forward to returning again soon and becoming better acquainted with the owners and staff and their changing menu. Don't wait, call and make your reservation now!< /text>

<UserId.>100851355236666113962< /UserId.>< user_name>
Nate Kotila</user_name>
<Date>1522987662463< /Date><Rating>3< /Rating>< Text>
Delicious food, with a very pleasing aesthetic.

Update 4/5/18:
On second visit the dinner was fairly bland. The menu was ambitious, but the dishes lacked flavor. I had a chicken stuffed with feta and sun-dried tomato, and my girlfriend had a beef pasta, both seemed like they were salt deficient and the pasta was overcooked.

Our appetizers were also fairly ambitious, hers was a bitter greens salad with prosciutto and a duck egg in which the flavors didn't quite mix. Mine was a mandarin and fennel salad that had good flavor but was very limp.

The wine selection was great, and the cider was quite delicious.

We did not have any desserts because they were out of the panna cotta at 7pm. The other desserts looked like they could be good, but just weren't appealing to us.

Overall, it was quite a let down tonight after being so great the first time as went in. However, the aesthetic is still nice and the sourdough focaccia they served upon seating us was delicious.< /Text>

< review>
Decent bubbles , beautiful view, but that's where it stops. I have been to Gloria Ferrer four times. The first time was amazing, which is why I decided to go back. Even though the service wasn't great on my second visit, I decided to join the wine club because I truly enjoyed the wines.

On visit three and four, the service dropped tremendously. Both times, I waited more than 30 minutes for service, despite having a reservation. On the final visit, I had an extremely poor experience and was then charged nearly $60 on a $50 bill due. While it was later explained that this tip was for the "full tasting" (discounted because I was a member), I was never told to expect this upfront, which is very disappointing. This was made more frustrating by the fact that we waited over 30 minutes to be seated, another 20 minutes for service once seated, and over 30 minutes to receive the bill. In fact, I never actually received the bill because we needed to leave, so my final payment was charged to the card on file. When I emailed to discuss my experience, ask about the 120% tip, and ask for club cancellation, no one responded except to cancel my membership. There was no apology or explanation for the poor service, and no one ever followed up.

Much of my frustration (and this one-star review) could've been avoided if someone from Gloria Ferrer had simply explained the circumstances behind the poor experience. Unfortunately, no one found it necessary to do so. I will no longer be going to Gloria Ferrer, and I would never recommend this winery to anyone that I know.< /review>

<rating>5<//rating>< name>
Morten Siersb√¶k</name>
<UserId.>110232890163003390488< /UserId.><Pics>None< /Pics>< Resp>
None< /Resp>
< Review>
We have come here 3 times so far, and have loved it each time. An excellent place for lovers of sparkly wines. Service has been very good with friendly and attentive waiters, and the building and the grounds are very nice with a wonderful expansive view from the terrace.

Food offerings are relatively simple for the most part but nice and tasty. They include cheese boards and charcuterie plates. They could upgrade and offer freshly baked bread instead (would love some baguettes), but at least the cheese and charcuterie are all very tasty and a good match for the wine.

Tasting flights are 3 x 2oz and cost around $ 25 to $ 35. You can also buy wine by the glass which is around $9-13 per glass. So it may actually be better value to buy individual glasses.

You can also buy bottles to go (and probably to drink as well), with prices ranging from around $20 for a very nice blanc de noirs to up to $80 or more, with the average being around $40-50.

We love this place and their excellent sparkly wine and will return again, no doubt!</Review>

< text>
Amazing 1st stop or last stop on the way in or out of Sonoma!  The hilltop view of the valley & marsh lands is beautiful and made even better over a bottle of sparkling wine at sunset.  The outdoor patio is rich with flowers and the accompanying hummingbirds which both mesmerize and enchant wine drinkers of all varietals...  Great deals on a bottle and complimentary spiced nuts are the norm but they offer far more in the way of great cheese and meat trays to delight all.</text>

<text>Gloria Ferrer was the last venue on our 4-day adventure to Napa and Sonoma. It was a "bucket list" trip for my sister and me. She lives in Las Vegas and I live near Boston and we have always been fans of Gloria Ferrer! Of all the vineyards we visited, Gloria Ferrer was the only one where took advantage of the tour. We were not disappointed in any way! Our tour guide, Tom, was cordial, accommodating knowledgeable and possessed a great sense of humor. Everyone we encountered at Gloria Ferrer, e.g. service personnel, tour guide and staff were amazing! I asked for a bag of ice to chill a bottle on the ride to San Francisco and the clerk was more than happy to provide the ice, albeit in a trash bag! Necessity is the mother of invention!
We loved everything about Gloria Ferrer: the vistas, the staff, the tour, the knowledgeable guide, Tom, the cheese plate and the history of this fascinating property. <user>105191890360076790971</user>< text>
I like Gloria Ferrer because you can do your tasting while seated at a table outside, allowing you to leisurely enjoy the view of the valley and vineyards instead of stuck inside, standing at a bar, staring at the wall. The Va di Va sparkling wine is amazing here--- it is so much better than anything else I've tried. I really wanted to buy a bottle, and in hindsight I should have, but it's such a pain traveling with alcohol. Visa Signature gets you two pre picked free pours. Awesome way to end a day of wine tasting. If I had more time in Sonoma, I would come here early on a warm day and just spend hours staring out at the valley, sipping on Va di Va and eating some cheese! Also love how clean and modern this place is. The bar inside is gorgeous and the bathrooms and overall decor of this place is beautiful.< /text>

1342476679435< /Date>
< Rate>
2<//Rate>
<Review>My wife and I were down in California doing some wine tasting in the Sonoma region. We found Gloria Ferrer from the VISA Signature Cardholder promotional guide. Under the guide wineries have the option to list benefits they will provide VISA signature card holders. On the guide it clearly stated that this place would offer complimentary wine tasting for cardholders, as opposed to discounts or other promotions that were also listed for various establishments on the guide.

We drove way out into the countryside to get there. They do NOT have a tasting room in the city, at least not that they advertised to us. When we got there it was a huge sprawling estate with several tour buses in front. I almost left then as it seemed like a typical cash-cow operation, much like you'd see over in neighboring Napa. However, since it was a very long drive to get there we decided to go inside.

Once inside we went to the "bar" and asked about tasting. An older gentleman that I would later find out to be named "Gary" informed us that there was a mistake, that there were no complimentary tastings for the VISA signature program and that all they offered were discounts, which were also listed on the brochure that I handed to him. Rather than argue with him we left. I phoned management and spoke with a woman who did not seem to understand my problem, so I was escalated to a guy named Dennis who left me a voice-mail.

On returning home from California I returned Dennis's call to ask him what he would do. Instead he kept asking me what I wanted him to do... He said he would speak to "Gary" and make sure it didn't happen again. Apparently they DO offer complimentary wine tastings to people but in a different manner, usually a larger tasting of a single wine rather than smaller pours of many wines. However, we did not get that.

I asked Dennis what he normally did in these situations and he said they usually comp. parties for their wine and give them a bottle to go home with. I explained I was not satisfied with him apologizing and he did not offer anything to me. I did not feel comfortable asking for anything since I did not want him to think I was trying to shake them down for free stuff. It was a very awkward conversation.

In summary, I do not recommend this place. In Dennis's own words, they are used to getting 700+ people a day on large tour buses. Avoid this cash-cow operation like the plague. I also plan on contacting VISA and letting them know about this.

If you are interested in wine tasting in the Sonoma area and/or you are part of the VISA signature program, then hit one of the other 70+ wineries participating. In all we only found 3 with problems and only 1 non-compliant. Many of them are small family-run wineries that are more interested in you as a person than you as one of 700+ walking money-bags that they can fleece for cash.< /Review><pictures>None< /pictures>< response>
None< /response>

<time>1610936353842<//time><Text>You have never had chicken fingers so crispy!!  Rarely eat these but when I do, Cane's is the only place to go.  Their sauce and sweet tea are great too!< /Text>< response>

< Pictures>

<user_name>Cynthia Diaz</user_name></record></dataset><record>
< review>
I love chicken strips, and this place does them very well. And their house sauce for dipping is the best sauce, full stop. I could drink it. But we're not here just for the sauce, right?

The chicken: cooked well, tastes fresh. Sometimes it has been a little dry, but in the same way that occurs when you leave it in the deep fryer a tad long. I've only had it that way a couple times, but beyond that it's been moist and perfect.

Fries: crinkle cut fries are my jam... And these are pretty good, but could use a crispier exterior.

The toast: every combo comes with this thick, buttery toast. It's tasty and a nice addition.

The ice: they have crushed ice, which is scientifically proven to make sodas more enjoyable.

Raising Cane's isn't from around here, and it definitely feels like it. In a good way. It's just a pleasant change of pace. Great place and you gotta try it!</review>

<date>1585074426339< /date><Resp>None<//Resp><Name>Marcus Oberlander</Name>< pics>
None<//pics>
<Review>Important!: I purchased food from this location in early February 2020.

While my wife and I were driving cross country from Maryland to California, we saw many Raising Cane's locations, especially in Tennessee. I found there was one not that far from where I now live in Orange County, California, and I thought I would give it a try.

The first thing is they only have a few combos on their menu depending on how many chicken fingers you order. I ordered the 3 Finger Combo, which consists of chicken fingers, 1 cup of Cane's sauce, fries, and Texas toast. You can make substitutions if you choose. Their chicken fingers were surprisingly great! They were tender and moist and the breading was seasoned perfectly. Even though it is fast food, they were not too oily. You should definitely dip them in the Cane's Sauce.

I have never seen a fry I do not like, and I was quite happy that they were served with crinkle fries. It worked well with the chicken tenders. I was happy that the combo included the Texas Toast also.

I was happy that I stopped here. The employees were friendly and helpful, and the food was delicious.</Review><rating>5<//rating>< gmap_id>

<GmapID>0x80dce8f222e70eb5:0x7a1438047cb3666d<//GmapID>< Review>
I love canes! Sometimes, it's worth the drive to get it because I crave their tender chicken and bread!

pros: chicken strips are very juicy and seasoned well, not too salty or overpowering, bread is buttery and complements chicken well

cons: sometimes the fries aren't that fresh or can be too soggy, and at times, the bread can be too oily sometimes (it's a hit or miss)

But overall, really like their chicken fingers here and the combination of chicken fingers, fries, and bread really does make a solid delicious meal!</Review>

< Review>
Great food, fast service, _terrible_ drive thru. This is one of the busiest intersections in Orange county. You can enter on northbound Carlota, or westbound El Toro, but if you enter on Carlota, you need to wind thru the lot to get to the back of the drive thru line, which requires cutting *thru* the line. In most cases those in line won't let you, because half the time some jerk just cuts into the line.<//Review>

Great food, their Texas toast is the best. I always sub the coleslaw for more toast. I wish there was some more options for what kind of spices were on the chicken and their staff is a bit too friendly and happy but nothing that takes away from the experience there.

The chicken is always perfectly cooked, the cane sauce is very good and pairs well with the tenders and combined with the Texas bread and fries you are looking at a huge meal. Something else that all the raising Cane's have is that they are open pretty late. This location is almost a little too tight though so be prepared for some tight manuvering.< /text>

<user_name>Luis P.< /user_name><text>Devin took our order. Nice guy, competent at his job. We ordered the combination with 3 Strips each. First time in the place, and curious as to how it could compare to Chick'Fille or something to that effect, which I think is overpriced and not that great. Order arrived piping hot and the strips look definitely bigger than I seen in a long time in a fast food. Fries were surprisingly tasty, and done almost to fries perfection. The slice of bread, which caught me my surprise but now can see how it complements the meal, nice and soft. Should have tried the coleslaw, which I was told by the family member that suggested the place, that is was a nice option. At first I thought that for 3 Chicken Strips and the $7 plus? we paid, was excessive, but after having this quick lunch, I was happy, and most important, filled for the afternoon duties.
Simple formula done well, now I am desiring to buy this strips individually at around $1.19 each, for the chicken in our case, tasted moist and flavorful. Unexpectedly nice this Raising Cane's Chicken Fingers. Worth revisiting when in the area, for I hear they are not spread out as of yet. 4 Stars.< /text></record></dataset><record>
